<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Draft Wales Bill</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Electoral Commission (DWB 09)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Electoral Commission is an independent body which reports directly to the UK Parliament. We regulate political party and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">election finance and set standards for well-run elections. We put voters first by working to support a healthy democracy, where elections and referendums are based on our principles of trust, participation, and no undue influence. We are responsible for pu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">blishing reports on the administration of elections</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and referendums</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ur comments on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">draft </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bill relate to matters concerning referendums and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">electoral arrangements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Referendum about commencement of income tax provisions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have specific responsibilit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in relation to the conduct of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">referendums held under the framework of the Political Parties, Elections and Referendums Act 2000 (PPERA). The proposed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">referendum included within the D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">raft Wales Bill</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">conducted under that framework.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In any such</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> referendum,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> our role includes:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Giving our views on the intelligibility of the referendum question</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Registering campaigners who want to spend significant amounts in the referendum</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Where appropriate, appointing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lead campaign groups for each outcome</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Providing lead campaign groups with grants that we determine within statutory limits</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Monitoring and taking steps necessary to ensure compliance with the rules on referendu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m expenditure and making public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> after the referendum how much registered campaigners </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">spent</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Making recommendations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on spendi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng limits for campaigners</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Promoting public awareness</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reporting on the referendum</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Chair of the Commission, or someone she appoints, is Chief Counting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Officer,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> responsible for the conduct of the referendum and ensur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing the accuracy of the overall result. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A well-run referendum which has the confidence of voters and campaigners is underpinned by a clear and certain legal framework. Good legislation provides absolute clarity on the roles and responsibilities of those a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dministering the referendum and sets out fair rules governing cam</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">paign spending and fundraising.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Commission’s comments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on the draft Bill</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">draw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on lessons learnt from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Wales and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the UK-wide referendum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> held in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We published reports on the two </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">referendums in 2011</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The legislation for the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> forthcoming</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Scottish independence referendum addresses a number of our recommendations from 2011 and also contains provisions specific to that referendum. After the independence referendum, we will reflect on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how those provisions have worked in practice and consider whether and how such provisions should apply to all referendums held under PPERA. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Rules for the conduct of the referendum</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The draft Bill provides f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or the referendum rules</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to be contained in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Orde</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r in Council</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The provision in the draft Bill is the same as that in the Government of Wales Act 2006</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (GOWA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Following the referendums in 2011, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we recommended</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the UK Government should use the powers pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vided </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the Political Parties, Elections and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Referendums Act 2000</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (PPERA) to make a generic order providing for the conduct of any future referendum</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We said that i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntroducing generic rules would:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Mean that the legislation specific to each particular referendum need concentrate only on the substanc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e of that referendum, when it will be held and the referendum question(s) to be asked of voters</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Speed up the legislative process, enabling a referendum to be held more quickly</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bring clarity for those planning to campaign in the referendum and for those run</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ning the referendum, and allow planning and preparation to commence sooner</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Remove any scope for amending rules for political reasons during the process of calling for a referendum.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Government responded to our recommendation in December 2012</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, recog</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the benefits that a generic conduct order for refe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rendums would bring, and undertaking to consider this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> further, including through discussion with the Law Commission in the context of their revi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ew of electoral law as a whole.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We continue to urge the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Government to make such an Order, which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in relation to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the draft Wales Bill would obvia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">te the need for rules to be made in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Order in Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> after the referendum h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as been triggered. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Having a generic conduct Order in place would also ensure that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rules for the referendum are in place at least six months before t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he referendum takes place, as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should be t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he case for all polls</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We have already seen the benefit of this for the Scottish independence referendum, where the relevant legislation is in place </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nine months in advance of the poll.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We recommend that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rules that apply to the conduct of a referendum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">under the provisions of the draft Bill </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">are in pl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ace at least six months before the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> referendum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">is held</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Scope of the Order-making power</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Notwithstanding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> our recommendation for a generic conduct order, we are concerned that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Order-making power in the draft Bill </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">may not be sufficient in scope to allow for lessons learnt fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">om other referendums</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to be applied</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our concern is based on experience in the previ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ous referendum in Wales in 2011.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The detailed rules </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for the referendum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">held under</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Parliamentary Voting Systems </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and Constituencies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2011</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (PVS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were very similar to the rules used for the Wales referendum in March 2011, but with some notable differe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nces. The two sets of referendum rules could not be fully aligned at the time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">because of limitations to the scope of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Order-making power in in GOWA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recommended that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">changes should be made to the ge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">neric</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> controls </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on campaigning at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> any referendum held under the provisions of PPERA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, to provide a robust and proportionate regulatory regime</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We recommend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, therefore, that these should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> apply to any referendum held under the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> provisions of the draft Bill. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Again b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ased on experience from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Wales referendum in 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it may not be possible for these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to be introduced under the O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rder-making power in its current form.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.18</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To illustrate the scope of the Order-making power</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that will be needed, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">specific examples that the rules for the referendu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m should include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the changes that need to be made to the regulatory controls of the referendum are set out in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Annex 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.19</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e recommend tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">t the Order-making power for a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> referendum in the draft Wales Bill should be sufficiently broad in scope to enable any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> recommendations about the conduct and regulation of referendums held under PPERA to apply to a referendum held under the provisions of the Bill. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.20</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If there is any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">doubt about whether the changes that are needed can be achieved through an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rder</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in Council, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hen we suggest that amendments are incorporated in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">primary legislation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Designation and putti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ng campaign arguments to voters</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.21</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he issue of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">whether the referendum is likely to stimulate a level of debate which would generate willing and a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ble applicants for designation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as lead campaigner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on both sides </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the argument </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is one that needs early consideration. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.22</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The generic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">statutory designation process </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in PPERA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">relies on the assumption that there will be campaign groups on either side of the re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ferendum question which are willing and able to use the benefits of designation to mount a lead campaign. If that is not the case – either because most prospective campaigners are on one side of the debate, or because a campaigner sees tactical advantage i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n not seeking designation – then the referendum campaign, and the process of putting the campaign arguments to voters, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is likely to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> suffer.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.23</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t the 2011 referendum in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Wales, we were unable to designate lead campaigners because there was no willing and able </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">applicant for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘no’ outcome.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.24</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We recommended</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 2011 that when considering the case for future referendums, legislators should take into account whether the referendum is likely to stimulate a level of debate which would generate willing and able appli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cants for designation. We would of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">course be happy to work with the Government to consider how to take th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is recommendation into account.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.25</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We also recommended</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 2011 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Government should take steps to reduce the potential advantages to a prospective l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ead campaigner of deciding not to apply for designation. In 2012, the Government responded to this recommendation by saying</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Designated organisations are important to the referendum process as they are a source of public awareness about the issues at hand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It is important that support be provided for them through the legislative framework. Clearly, it runs counter to the interests of voters if there is any incentive for campaigners to refrain from applying to become designated organisations, as this may im</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pede the proper development of public understanding during a referendum campaign…… The Government is therefore considering carefully how the designation process might be improved</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.26</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Scottish Government has addressed this recommendation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scottish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Independence Referendum Act 2013 by providing for the Commission to designate for only one outcome if there are not willing and abl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e applicants for both outcomes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">180-day timetable for the Order in Council</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.27</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he draft </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bill</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> provides for a 180-day period from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> receipt by t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Secretary of State </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of a notice from the First Mi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nister </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o the draft Order </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">being laid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in Parliament</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This compares with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">120-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">day period </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">GOWA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in practice suspended after</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> UK Parliamentary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> general election</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> was held</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y 201</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.28</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As described earlier, generic referendum rules would obviate the need for referendum rules to be made by Order in Council. Without generic rules, however, advance drafting of the rules will be essential to enable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">statutory consultation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and others, as well as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> scrutiny,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> within the 180-day timetable.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.29</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">80-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">day period will include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the time the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ommission needs to undertake our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> statutory assessmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the intelligibility of the referendum question</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our approach to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assessing ref</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erendum questio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">take</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10 weeks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to complete, which includes time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to undertake public opinion research to see what people think of the question</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. We need time to undertake any necessary procurement and about two weeks’ notice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">start </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">test</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the que</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.30</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oll</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owing receipt of our assessment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the referendum question, the Secretary of State wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ll need time to consider our recommendations. It is possible that further iterations will be required </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">before the question</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> can be finalised for inclusion in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">der in Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.31</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The 180-day period should allow sufficient time for assessing and finalising the referendum question for inclusion in the Order in Counci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l, providing advance preparation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is undertaken. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Legislative timetable</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.32</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For completeness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">highlight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the need for early consideration of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> timetable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the referendum itself</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We recommended</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> after the referendums held</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at least 12 weeks between the campaign rules being finalised and the start of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">regulated referendum peri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">od. This period is important to enable the Commission to publish and disseminate guidance in time to allow campaigners to understand the rules before they come into force. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Voter information</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.33</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Draft Wales Bill</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> provides for the Commission to have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> respons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ibi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lity for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">providing informatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n to voters. The provisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> mirror</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of GOWA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2006 and we are content with their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> inclusion</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">National Assembly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for Wales electoral arrangements</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">year fixed terms</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.34</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he draft Bill</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would lengthen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Assembly terms from four to five years. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst the C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ommission does not have a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">specific </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">view on the question of whether an Assembly term should be a four or five year fixed term, we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">give</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">views on particular combinations of elections.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Commission’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s position is that each individual proposal should b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e considered on its merits and w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e advise on the particular risks and how they could be managed.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our priority is that a poll</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is well-run and delivered in a way that is easy for voters to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">understand and par</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ticipate in.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.35</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The election schedule is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2016 – Police and Crime Commissioner Elections and Welsh general election</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2020 – UK Parliamentary general election; Police a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd Crime Commissioner elections;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Welsh general election</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> if four-year term</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2021 – Wales local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">government elections</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Welsh general election</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> if five-year term</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.36</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The combination of a UK Parliamentary general election, Welsh general election and Police and Crime Commissioner elections in 2020 would present significan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t challenges for voters. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t would mea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n each voter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">casting ballots</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in up to three differently-drawn constituencies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an electoral region;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on four separate ballot papers and using</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">three different electoral systems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It would also prove challenging for political parties and candidates, not least because of the risk of one campaign overshadowing another and the communication issues that campaigning across multiple elections presents. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There would also be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dministrative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">challenges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Ret</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">urning Off</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">icers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Overall, these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> issues would bring significant risks to ensuring well-run elections.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.37</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Moving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Assembly term to five years avoids </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the risks inherent in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">combining three sets of elections i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n 2020</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, although </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">does then bri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">combination with local government elections</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in 2021</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at combination, each voter would cast ballots</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a constituency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an electoral region</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a local ward</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, on three ballot papers and using two electoral systems. There would be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">risks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to add</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ress</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, but less so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2020.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Restore the right for candidates to stand on both a constituency and regional list during the Assembly elections</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.38</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he draft </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bill</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> provides for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the removal of the restriction on standing for election for both cons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tituency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">electoral regions.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should be straightforward for people to participate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in elections, whether voting or campaigning. This means there should be no unnecessary barriers to standing for election. We made our view clear when the initial proposals to prohibit dual candidacy in W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ales were published as part of the Government of Wales Bill 2006 that we did not believe that the case for introducing the change had been made, on the evidence available at the time. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.39</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To our knowledge, no further evidence has become available that would s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uggest that the prohibition should be retained. It continues to be the case that there is no similar prohibition for candidates in Scottish Parliament elections, where the same electoral system is in use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  We agree, therefore, that candidates should be abl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e to stand in a constituency and a region in the same Assembly election. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ensure that Assembly Members cannot be MPs at the same time</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.40</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he draft </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bill</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> provides for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the disqualification of MPs from membership of the Assembly. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While we do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> not have a specific </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">view on the question</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of multiple mandates, issues to be considered are what the electorate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> expect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s of their representatives and how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">representative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ensure the best possible leve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Can this be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> achieved by representing the electorate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at a variety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of different levels (for example at the UK Parliament and the National Assembly for Wales) and the experience which this brings about or should the focus be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> entirely on one legislature?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#003366; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Annex 1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Recommended changes to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">conduct and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">regulation of PPERA referendums</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.41</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To illustrate the scope of the Order-making power</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that will be needed, below are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">specific examples </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of what</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the rules for the referendum should include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the changes that we recommend </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the regulatory controls </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in PPERA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">referendum campaigns.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Rules for the conduct of the referendum</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The rules should be as contained in the Parliamentary Voting Systems and Constituencies Act 2011, including:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A power for the Chief Counting Officer to app</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oint a Deputy Chief Counting Officer</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A power for the Chief Counting Officer to give directions to the Deputy Chief Counting Officer and local Counting Officers about the discharge of their functions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local Counting O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fficers (equivalent to local election Re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">turning Officers) to be appointed by statute (rather than by individual contractual letters of appointment from Chief Counting Officer)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A power of the Chief Counting Officer to specify modifications to the format, layout and wording of key voter-facing ref</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erendum forms and notices to make them easier for voters to understand and use</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Clarification that local counting officers should be excluded from the restriction on the publication of promotional material about the referendum, in the same way that the Elec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">toral Commission is excluded.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Regulation of referendum campaigns</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ppropriate ‘acting in concert’ provisions taking into account the lessons from the 2011 voting systems referendum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to strengthen the rules that prevent multiple campaigners being established</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to circumvent the spending limits, whilst reducing the burdens on small campaigners. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013 contains</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> improvements to the ‘acting in concert’ provisions from those that applied in 2011. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Subject to the lessons learned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from the Scottish referendum, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we recommend that those provisions be used for future referendums.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ontrols on the permissibility and reporting of loans, in the same way as for donations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">PPERA includes a power to introduce generic controls on loans to refe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rendum campaigners but this has not yet been used. The rules for the parliamentary voting systems referendum in 2011 and the upcoming Scottish independence referendum both include controls on loans. We have recommended that these rules should apply to all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">future PPERA referendums.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Improve the information about campaign funding that is available to voters before they cast their vote by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">providing for pre-poll reporting of donations and loans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Scottish referendum will be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the first referendum in the UK at w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hich there will be statutory pre-poll reporting of donations and loans to campaigners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Subject to the lessons learned from that referendum, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we recommend that those provisions be used for future referendums.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Clarify that press comment is not subject to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">spending controls</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to bring the referendum rules in line with those that apply at elections. In its 2012 response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to our recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the Government agreed that this exclusion should apply at future referendums. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Confirm that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">it would be inappropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for the Commission to have any role in policing the truthfulness of referendum campaign arguments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In its 2012 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to our recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the Government suppo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rted the Commission’s position.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Clarify the scope of the restriction on publication of materi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">al by publicly funded organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In its 2012 response, the Government responded that it was considering the effectiveness and enforceability of this provision.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.42</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Parliamentary Voting System and Constituencies Act 2011, our 2011 referendum report, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the Scott</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ish Independence Referendum Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2013 also contained a number of other proposed amendments to the generic PPERA controls which reduce the burdens on campaigners and improve the workability and clarity of the rules. There would be considerable b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enefit in these amendments also applying at future PPERA referendums to:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Supplement the controls against establishing multiple campaigners by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">providing that the same person cannot be the responsible person for more than one registered campaigner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reduce th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e costs and burdens on campaigners by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">changing the process for dealing with late claims from requiring a court application to being an application to the Commission for permission to pay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">educe the burdens on campaigners that register but then do not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">spend over the registration threshold by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">introducing a declaration of spending rather than requiring a full spending return</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If a designation process is to be used, then it will also be important to consider:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Moving the designation process to before the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">start of the referendum period</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as at the Scottish independence referendum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This will give certainty to both campaigners and voters and give the designated lead campaigners the maximum amount of time to make use of the benefits available to them. If the le</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gislative timetable is such that early designation is not possible, then our recommendation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">extend the length of the referendum period </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to at least 16 weeks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to give designated lead campaign groups more time to plan and use the benefits available to them </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be adopted.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:18.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Strengthening the controls on the distribution of public funds by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">clarifying that the Commission can pay grants to designated lead campaign groups in instalments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In its 2012 response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to our recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the Government confirmed that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it would expect to provide a similar option at future referendums. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">New recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.43</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">During 2011-12 the Commission undertook a review of the of the UK’s party and election finance laws</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We recommended new measures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to simplify the registration process, provide more detailed reporting of pre-registration spending, requiring imprints on electronic material and improvements to the workability of the provisions around sanctioning and late payment of fines. We would of c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ourse be happy to work with the Government to take these new recommendations forward.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#003366; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Part 2, sections 10 and 11; Schedule 1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Reports on the Referendum on the voting system for UK Parliamentary elections (</span><a href="http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/141328/Final-PVS-report.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/141</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">328/Final-PVS-report.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">) and the Referendum on the law-making powers of the National Assembly for Wales (</spa